# What is the -o Flag?

The `-o` flag stands for:

```text
Output Format
```

It tells Kubernetes how to display the command output.

### Syntax

```bash
kubectl get <resource> -o <format>
```

Example:

```bash
kubectl get pods -o wide
```

---

# Common Output Formats

## Default Output

```bash
kubectl get pods
```

Output:

```text
NAME      READY   STATUS
nginx     1/1     Running
```

---

## -o wide

Shows additional details.

```bash
kubectl get pods -o wide
```

Output:

```text
NAME    READY   STATUS    IP            NODE
nginx   1/1     Running   10.244.0.5    worker-1
```

### Additional Information

* Pod IP
* Node Name
* Internal networking details

---

## -o yaml

Displays complete resource definition.

```bash
kubectl get pod nginx -o yaml
```

Useful for:

* Debugging
* Understanding object structure
* Learning Kubernetes

---

## -o json

Displays the object in JSON format.

```bash
kubectl get pod nginx -o json
```

Useful for:

* Automation
* APIs
* Scripting

---

## -o name

Displays only resource names.

```bash
kubectl get pods -o name
```

Output:

```text
pod/nginx
pod/redis
```

---

## -o custom-columns

Display selected fields.

```bash
kubectl get pods \
-o custom-columns=NAME:.metadata.name,STATUS:.status.phase
```

Output:

```text
NAME    STATUS
nginx   Running
redis   Running
```

---

## -o jsonpath

Extract specific information.

Get Pod IP:

```bash
kubectl get pod nginx \
-o jsonpath='{.status.podIP}'
```

Output:

```text
10.244.0.5
```

Get all Pod names:

```bash
kubectl get pods \
-o jsonpath='{.items[*].metadata.name}'
```

---

# Most Commonly Used -o Formats

| Format         | Purpose                  |
| -------------- | ------------------------ |
| wide           | Extra details            |
| yaml           | Complete YAML definition |
| json           | Complete JSON definition |
| name           | Resource names only      |
| custom-columns | Custom output            |
| jsonpath       | Extract specific fields  |

